            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </table-wrap>
      <p>There are thirty three clearly reported cases of primary osseous lymphoma at either single or multiple sites, in all ages, in the scientific literature since 1927. Table <xref ref-type="table" rid="T2">2</xref> details these 32 cases as well as this current case. It does not include patients who presented with disease at non osseous and osseous sites, or those patients in whom hodgkins disease disseminated to the bone. At least 7 of these cases were reported prior to 1954 when CT, MRI and PET scanning was not available, so it cannot be stated for certain, whether these cases had any evidence of lymphadenopathy within the chest or abdomen. We are uncertain therefore, whether these are true cases of POHL.</p>
